<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level CREATE ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_agent` UNCONDITIONAL create access
    on the `x_casemgmt_case` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_casemgmt`. This is the CREATE companion to the sibling READ ACL at
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml and the WRITE ACL at
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_agent_assigned.xml; together with the
    case_manager-specific ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml, the case-
    table create-permission set is fully and exhaustively realized for the
    three scoped roles (manager: yes; agent: yes; viewer: deny-by-default).

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_agent row:
          | Role                  | Create | Read              | Write             | Delete |
          | x_casemgmt_case_agent  |  Yes   | Yes Assigned only | Yes Assigned only |  No    |
        This file authors the single "Create = Yes" cell. The "Yes Assigned
        only" Read cell is authored by ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml;
        the "Yes Assigned only" Write cell by
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_write_agent_assigned.xml; the "No" Delete cell
        is enforced by the deliberate ABSENCE of any
        x_casemgmt_case_delete_agent.xml file (ServiceNow record-level ACLs
        are deny-by-default: a role with no granting ACL for an operation
        cannot perform that operation). Each row of the ACL matrix maps to
        exactly one or zero ACL XML files; this per-cell granularity is what
        lets the Update Set add or remove role privileges independently
        without entangling roles or operations.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - all-roles create coverage:
          - case_manager: Create=Yes  -> ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml
          - case_agent:   Create=Yes  -> THIS FILE
          - case_viewer:  Create=No   -> deliberate absence of any ACL
        Together these three facts implement the user prompt's contract that
        both managers and agents can submit cases, but the lowest-privilege
        viewer (audit / compliance / supervisor tier) cannot.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
          "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write; case_agent
           cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has full access."
        The clause "case_agent cannot access UNASSIGNED cases" applies to
        read and write only - it is logically inapplicable to create because
        a record cannot be "assigned" to anyone before it exists. Therefore
        this ACL grants create unconditionally to any caller holding the
        x_casemgmt_case_agent role; downstream visibility of the created
        record is governed by the read/write _agent_assigned siblings.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This ACL is the table-level CREATE binding for the mid-tier
        scoped role.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): The ServiceNow target replaces
        ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.getRolesToPrivileges() (a
        Map<String, List<Object>> bound from application.rolesToPrivileges
        configuration) and AcmPluginUrlPrivilege URL-method enforcement
        with declarative scoped record-level ACLs. This XML record is
        therefore the declarative equivalent of the conceptual
        (case_agent, CREATE) cell of that ArkCase map.
      - Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine Transition Map): Cases are born in
        Draft. The state machine then drives Draft -> Open -> In Progress
        -> (Pending) -> Resolved -> Closed. Without this CREATE ACL the
        agent role would have no way to insert a new case row, and the
        Draft entry point of the state machine would be unreachable from
        the agent surface (only managers could ever start a case). The
        AAP explicitly requires both manager AND agent to be able to
        create cases (Section 0.5.6); this ACL realizes the agent half.
      - Section 0.7.4 (Other User-Provided Rules) - "Cases created,
        assigned, progressed through all defined states, and closed via
        both internal UI and external portal." This success-criterion
        bullet implies that authenticated case_agent users must be able
        to create cases via the internal native form view. THIS ACL is
        what makes that path permitted.

    Why <advanced>false</advanced> (in contrast to read/write _agent_assigned):
      The READ and WRITE agent-assigned siblings use <advanced>true</advanced>
      so the platform invokes their CDATA scripted condition that evaluates
      "current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID() OR current is in current
      user's group memberships." That predicate cannot be evaluated at
      create time because no `current` record exists yet - the row is being
      inserted at the moment the ACL fires. The platform binds `current` to
      a freshly-instantiated record skeleton with the caller's POSTed field
      values, and assigned_agent / assigned_group on that skeleton are
      typically null (or whatever the form defaulted them to) - making any
      "Assigned only" check meaningless and noisy. Per the AAP design
      pattern in Section 0.4.3 the "Assigned only" predicate is reserved
      for read/write ACLs; create is a binary role check.
      Consequences of <advanced>false</advanced>:
        - <condition/>  is evaluated as an empty encoded query (no row
                        filter; permits the request).
        - <script/>     is NOT evaluated (the platform skips it when
                        advanced=false).
        - <roles>       remains the sole admission gate: callers holding
                        x_casemgmt_case_agent are granted create; callers
                        without the role are denied.
      This is the standard ServiceNow pattern for "any role member can
      perform this operation, no per-row predicate" and matches the agent
      prompt's "create has no condition" rule verbatim.

    Why creation is unconditional (and what governs the created row afterward):
      Pre-creation there is no record to evaluate against - any "row-level"
      check is logically impossible. Once the record is inserted, downstream
      access is governed by:
        (a) The read/write _agent_assigned ACLs (siblings of this file),
            which restrict the creating agent's subsequent visibility of
            and edits to their own freshly-created case to the rows where
            they are the assigned_agent or a member of the assigned_group.
        (b) The field-level ACL on `assigned_group`
            (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml), which
            restricts WRITE on the assigned_group column to the
            x_casemgmt_case_manager role only - an agent who creates a case
            therefore cannot self-assign it to a group at create time. The
            new case lands in the database with assigned_group = null, which
            (per AAP Section 0.5.5) corresponds to the Draft state.
        (c) The before-insert business rule
            ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_opened_date.xml, which auto-
            populates opened_date = gs.nowDateTime() on every successful
            insert.
        (d) The before-update business rule
            ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml,
            which (later, when the manager assigns a group/agent) enforces
            that assigned_agent is a member of assigned_group.
      In short: an agent CAN create a case but cannot self-promote the new
      record out of Draft. Promotion to Open requires the manager-only
      assigned_group field-level ACL grant, which then unlocks the Open
      transition rule per AAP Section 0.5.5. This composition of create-ACL
      + field-ACL is the AAP's design for letting agents file cases without
      bypassing the manager's queue-assignment authority.

    Why a separate file per role (instead of one create ACL with both roles):
      ServiceNow allows multiple roles in a single <roles> field as a comma-
      separated list, and that pattern technically also satisfies the AAP.
      However, the established convention in this Update Set (and in
      industry practice for scoped applications) is one ACL record per
      (table, operation, role) triple. Reasons:
        - Single-responsibility: each ACL record encodes exactly one
          authorization fact; if the AAP later removes case_agent's create
          privilege (e.g., to enforce a stricter intake-via-portal-only
          policy), the change is a single-file deletion with no risk of
          accidentally also revoking case_manager's create privilege.
        - Auditability: the file inventory under ../acl/ becomes a
          self-documenting matrix - the presence or absence of a file
          named x_casemgmt_<table>_<operation>_<role>.xml is the answer
          to "does role X have privilege Y on table Z?".
        - Update Set diff clarity: when the Update Set is re-imported on
          a fresh PDI, each ACL is a discrete row in the preview screen,
          making it easy to spot that case_agent's create privilege was
          installed (alongside case_manager's) versus a single combined
          row that would obscure the role membership.
      The companion ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml file
      authors the case_manager half of the Create=Yes pair using the
      same per-role-per-operation pattern.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section 0.3.2;
    no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/services/
        users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration
        map (`Map<String, List<Object>> rolesToPrivileges`) keyed by the
        property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that model, an
        "agent-equivalent" role would have been associated with privilege
        identifiers such as `acm-case-create` or `acm-case-add`, and those
        privilege strings would have been resolved at runtime against
        URL-method bindings declared in
        ApplicationPluginPrivilegesConfig.getApplicationPluginsPrivileges()
        via AcmPluginUrlPrivilege. The ServiceNow target replaces this
        bifurcated model (declarative privilege list + imperative URL-
        binding) with a single declarative scoped record-level ACL: this
        XML record IS the (case_agent, CREATE) cell of that conceptual map.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/com/
        armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        plus the role-name normalization step that uppercased the role,
        replaced whitespace with underscores, replaced periods with
        double-underscores, and prepended the `ROLE_` prefix from
        RolePrivilegesConstants). All of this Java service surface is
        replaced in the ServiceNow target by the platform's built-in
        sys_security_acl evaluator and by static role names declared in
        scope-prefixed sys_user_role records (the case_agent role is
        declared in ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml; this
        ACL references it by literal name in the <roles> field).

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package =
        x_casemgmt). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_casemgmt_case (NOT the OOB `task`
        table or any other global table), and <roles> references the
        scoped role x_casemgmt_case_agent. Per AAP Section 0.3.2 "Global
        scope changes of any kind" are explicitly prohibited.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name /
        source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The <sys_id>
        below is THIS record's own deterministic primary key (MD5 of the
        canonical identifier "x_casemgmt_case.create.case_agent", a stable
        key for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to any other
        record. Computing the sys_id deterministically guarantees the ACL
        is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs and round-trip
        Update Set previews per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7.
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case` with NO
        dot. ServiceNow's create operation has no concept of "create this
        specific column" - field-level ACLs apply only to read/write/none.
        The <type>record</type> field below confirms this is a row-level
        (table-level) ACL, not a UI/REST/SOAP-flavored ACL.
      - Operation = create: corresponds exactly to the "Create = Yes" cell
        in the AAP matrix for the case_agent role.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required so
        platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or seed scoped
        data (per AAP Section 0.7.4 the seed_demo_data.js script seeds
        cases under the platform's elevated context). It does NOT widen
        case_agent privileges - case_agents without admin still see
        exactly what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = false: see "Why advanced=false" rationale above. The
        platform skips the empty <script/> body entirely.
      - condition (empty): the <condition/> encoded-query field is empty;
        no row-level filter applies (and none is meaningful pre-insert).
      - script (empty): the <script/> field is empty; the platform skips
        it because advanced=false.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml (resolves <name>x_casemgmt_case</name>)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles> by role name)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_agent.xml
          (the demo agent's create access during round-trip verification
          depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml (demo cases inserted
          by the seed pass need this ACL in place if any seed runs under
          the demo agent's identity context; the seed_demo_data.js script
          itself runs as admin so admin_overrides bypasses this ACL during
          seeding, but post-seed agent-side smoke tests against the demo
          dataset depend on this ACL being applied)
        - ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_submit.xml (the
          scripted REST endpoint for the external portal runs server-side
          under the platform context, so it does not strictly depend on
          this agent-role ACL for its insert; however the ACL is loaded
          earlier in the Update Set anyway because the scripted REST and
          its handler script are loaded after all ACLs)

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used verbatim per AAP convention (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"). ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
    scope id is concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier
    is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped application. The deterministic sys_id below is computed against the
    `casemgmt` literal and remains stable across re-imports onto fresh PDIs.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>false</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Table-level ACL: x_casemgmt_case_agent can create x_casemgmt_case records (no condition; assignment is governed by separate ACLs).</description>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case</name>
        <operation>create</operation>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
        <script/>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>8ae51c961898321cb00dc4018d7e88d5</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_case</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_create_agent</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>
